title: For Sale:  Bergara B-14 HMR 6.5 Creedmoor
postcontent:
This is a great rifle that I only picked up a few weeks ago, but an unexpected home construction project has gotten in the way.
I bought it from Bass Pro in Kodak.  It has had less than 80 rounds through it as I am still in the process of breaking it in.  Shoots sub MOA with Factory Match ammo.  Love the rifle but have to install a sewer pump.  I shot a 1000 yard clinic at ORSA with it and it was very accurate at that distance.  I was consistantly in the 10 ring on a 20 shot string, with quite a few X's.  The trigger is outstanding. 
It comes along with the box and everything that came in it.  One 5 Round Magazine, 20MOA Scope Base, thread protector, etc.  Below is the description from BassPro'w website.  I am including a set of 30MM rings with it (worth $100), but the pictured scope is NOT included.
 www.basspro.com/shop/en/bergara-b-14-hmr-bolt-action-rifle
The Bergara® B-14 HMR Bolt-Action Rifle uses a world-renowned Bergara barrel with a state-of-the-art action and stock to produce a long range precision bolt-action rifle, capable of engaging targets at maximum range. The Bergara action utilizes a 2-lug system with a Sako-style extractor and a coned bolt nose and breech to ensure smooth feeding and flawless extraction. A Bergara curved trigger, set at 3 pounds, delivers a crisp, clean break. The receiver is drilled and tapped to fit Remington 700 style rings and bases. The barreled-action is solidly bedded in a Bergara HMR molded stock with a full-length, integrated mini-chassis that supports a fully free-floated barrel. The butt-stock has an adjustable cheek piece and length-of-pull; a near vertical pistol grip accommodates shooting from the prone position. The stock comes equipped with integrated QD flush cup sling mounts. The #5-contoured barrel is made of 4140 CrMo steel and finished in matte blue. The muzzle is threaded 5/8-24" and includes a thread protector. The Bergara B-14 HMR Bolt-Action Rifle uses a standard AICS detachable magazine (comes with one 5-round mag).
 -World-renowned 22" threaded Bergara barrel
-Bergara 2-lug action
-Sako-style extractor
-Free-floated barrel
-AICS detachable magazine
-Molded stock with integrated mini-chassis
-Adjustable for comb height and length of pull

-9.25 pounds

title: For Sale:  Customized Benelli M4 with TONS of extras
postcontent: Selling my customized Benelli M4. I purchased it in the summer of 2016 from Firing Line in Westland, MI. Originally, it came with the standard "rifle" buttstock, however I purchased a pistol-grip buttstock (currently on the gun) and a telescoping pistol-grip buttstock as well; both are factory Benelli parts and both extra stocks are included. Also replaced were the bolt-release and charging handle- it's now equipped with a GG & G Oversized Bolt-Release and GGG Oversized Charging Handle. The shotgun also has a "DG Parkerized" Carrier Comp Full Length Extended Magazine tube on it (so you don't have to wait 2-3 months for them to make ya one!). Instead of the factory picatinny rail that came on the gun (also included), there is a Scalarworks SYNC mount & Trijicon RMR RM06 Type 2 Combo (a very hard-to-obtain item on the scalarworks website). It's also got a Streamlight Protac 2 weapon light (with pressrue switch), and heavy duty cobra-buckled sling from Blue Force Gear that are already attached and included as well. On the flat side of the reciever there is a strip of velcro used to attach cordura/nylon "side saddles" for extra ammo; the few I have, I will include also.  All in all I have just over $3000.00 into the gun, as described above.I will also included the remaining premium-grade ammo I have, valued at about $500: appx 225 shells of Winchester Ranger Low Recoil 2 3/4 00 buckshot, 250 shells of Winchester Law Enforcement 2 3/4 12-pellet 00 buck, and 200 shells of Federal Premium Law Enforcement 2 3/4 9-pellet buckshot. I also have around 150 shells of miscellaneous other premium grade shells laying around that I'll put into a plastic ammo can and give you as well. The shotgun has around 300 rounds through it, is clean as a whistle, and is in great shape. The Trijcion RMR has a chip on the housing from where a training course I took last summer; the sight is in perfect working order but if the chip is an issue, I will keep the Trijicon (not the SYNC mount) and knock $250 off the package price. The Trijicon/SYNC Mount is a combo offered from the Scalarworks website and is sometimes very hard to obtain due to limited batches. Personally, I wouldn't seperate the two, but it's your call.My total value invested, as described, sits in the neighborhood of $3600. I'm not looking to trade, however if someone came out of the woodworks with a knock-my-socks-off offer (eg new Wilson Combat in 9mm) I would entertain that, but I'm primarily looking to get $2800, cash, with everything included, or $2550 without the Trijicon RMR. Thanks for checking out the ad - Jeff
